\begin_layout Standard
The pre-salt region, in addition to its oil potential, is characterized
 by the presence of carbonate deposits from the 'Pre-Salt' petroleum play,
 of which the Barra Velha Formation is a part 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "amorim2021analise"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosa2006engenharia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discuss that most commercially used oil reserves are formed in deposits
 in reservoirs composed of sedimentary rocks, both clastic and non-clastic,
 with sandstones and limestones being the most predominant.
 However, other types of rocks can also exhibit sufficient porosity to be
 considered important reservoirs.
 In these cases, porosity may result from interstitial spaces, although
 it is often attributed to the existence of fractures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For oil to be stored in the reservoir rock, it is essential that the rock
 has porosity, allowing it to retain the fluid, as well as permeability,
 a fundamental characteristic.
 Permeability determines the capacity of the porous medium to allow fluid
 passage, acting as a measure of fluid conductivity in a material.
 The evaluation of porosity and permeability plays a crucial role in describing
 a reservoir and defining flow patterns, aiming to improve oil production
 efficiency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosa2006engenharia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Carbonate rocks have characteristics that give them high complexity.
 In addition to difficulties in evaluating rock properties, many carbonates
 exhibit lateral structural heterogeneities, admitting, therefore, high
 variation in rock properties throughout the field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "al2010resolving"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characterization of porosity in geological materials plays a fundamental
 role in various applications, from the exploration of natural resources
 to the manufacture of industrial products 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Analitical-Methods-Webb"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Barra Velha Formation is composed of carbonate rock deposits found in
 the area of the petroleum play known as the 'Pre-salt.' The Santos Basin,
 in turn, can be classified as a passive continental margin basin and undergoes
 three distinct tectonostratigraphic evolutionary phases: the rift phase,
 followed by the post-rift phase, and finally, the drift phase.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moreira2007bacia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a lithostratigraphic perspective, the Barra Velha Formation occupies
 the basal sedimentary sequence of the post-rift phase and was divided by
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moreira2007bacia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 into two depositional sequences, the lower and upper, separated by a regionally
 significant unconformity at the basin scale.
 As highlighted by these authors, this formation, of Eoaptian age, is characteri
zed by limestone/laminite of microbial origin, stromatolites, and microbialites
 that are either partially or entirely dolomitized.
 It is also rich in talc and magnesian clays in the proximal portions and
 carbonate shales in the distal portions, deposited over the Pré-Alagoas
 unconformity.
 On the other hand, the upper Barra Velha Formation, of Neoaptian age, consists
 of conglomeratic-arenitic alluvial fans in the proximal portions and stromatoli
tic limestones and microbial laminite, locally dolomitized, in the distal
 portions of the basin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "artagao2018analise"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, precise analysis of pore size distribution is crucial to understandin
g the feasibility and potential use of these materials.
 In this work, a study will be developed to analyze the pore size distribution
 of the Barra Velha Formation, located in the Santos Basin, using the Mercury
 Intrusion Porosimetry (MIP) technique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "leon98"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 emphasizes the experimental speed and significant relevance of mercury
 porosimetry, highlighting its ability to assess multiple properties in
 a single sample.
 He also concludes that pore size distribution is one of the most promising
 models for this technique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "giesche2006mercury"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 clarifies that mercury porosimetry identifies pore size according to the
 pressure applied to the sample, meaning larger pore throat diameters are
 identified at low pressures, and vice versa.
 Additionally, he found that the smallest pore size identified in this analysis
 is 3.5 nm in diameter, at a maximum pressure of 60,000 psi.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "madonna2013synchrotron"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 examined the porosity of the rock specimens using 3D images produced by
 X-ray tomography and concluded that, in the samples under scrutiny, fluid
 movement within the rock primarily occurred through macropores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yu2014quantitative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explored the porous structure using electron microscopy and mercury porosimetry
 and determined that carbonate samples with over 50% of the porous network
 comprised of micropores influenced permeability.
 Nonetheless, this portion had negligible or minimal impact on permeability
 in this particular investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "archilha2015quantificaccao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 noted that microporosity did not emerge as a primary factor in permeability
 prediction based on the dataset analyzed, implying that other factors play
 a more significant role.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the aforementioned studies, this thesis will categorize pore throat
 sizes determined through mercury porosimetry into micropores (<0.5μm), mesopores
 (0.5 - 5μm), and macropores (>5μm) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "archie1942electrical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem Scope
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Escopo do Problema
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Escopo-do-Problema"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In light of the significant discovery of the pre-salt in the Santos Basin,
 specifically in the Barra Velha Formation, it becomes imperative to conduct
 a detailed analysis of the pore size distribution in this formation.
 The use of Mercury Intrusion Porosimetry (MIP) emerges as the primary approach
 to achieve this objective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scope of this work focuses on the application of MIP as a fundamental
 tool to assess the porosity of the Barra Velha Formation.
 The main emphasis lies in the analysis of pore size distribution, a crucial
 step in understanding the viability and potential use of these materials.
 The classification of pores into micropores, mesopores, and macropores
 will be an integral part of the analysis process, with the intention of
 categorizing and comprehending the porous structure at different scales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To achieve such classification, various models will be employed, with the
 Washburn Model standing out as a specific tool to describe the dynamics
 of mercury intrusion into fine pores.
 Understanding these intrusion patterns will not only provide valuable insights
 into pore distribution but also enable a more precise characterization
 of the porosity of the Barra Velha Formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the end of this study, the expectation is to not only provide a comprehensive
 analysis of pore size distribution but also contribute to a broader understandi
ng of the porous properties of this specific geological formation.
 This contribution has the potential to directly influence future strategies
 for exploration and oil production in this strategic region of the Santos
 Basin.
\end_layout

